paragraphs.text:
%md
####Accessing the data
For this example we will be again using the NASA MERRA reanalysis daily mean surface air temperature dataset. The difference will be that the data now lies in a directory on HDFS. We the SciSparkContext's NetcdfDFSFile to read netcdf files off of HDFS.

The spatial resolution is 0.5 degrees latitude by 0.67 degrees longitude, with a temporal coverage of 1979-2011. The raw data has already been subset into one quarter of the globe primarily spanning North America and includes only days falling in January. 
An exercise left to the users, is to actually do the subsetting using a sequence of maps and reduces the original netcdf dataset.

%md
####Data Prep using SciSpark
We follow a similar steps using SciSpark to detrend the dataset. Note that these lambda function inside the map function, is quite a bit more verbose.
This is primarily because nd4j (our backend array and linear algebra library) does not support broadcast operations in the version we are using.
Instead we had to rely on a for loop to subtract the mean-grid from each year.

%md
####Calculating Standard Deviation and Skewness 
The SciTensor datastructure allows us to take the standard deviation and skewness along a dimension.
We can also insert it back into the SciTensor dictionary.
At the end we do a collect operation to bring our computed data back to the head node.
This is also our first "action" call on an RDD, so it will execute the DAG of operations we have built.

paragraphs.text:
val calc_moments = detrendedRDD.map(p => {
    print(p)
    val std = p.std(Array(0)).tensor
    val skw = p.skew(Array(0)).tensor
    p.insertVar("std", std)
    p.insertVar("skw", skw)
    p
}).collect

paragraphs.text:
val std = calc_moments(0)("std").tensor.data
val skw = calc_moments(0)("skw").tensor.data
val latarr = calc_moments(0)("lat").tensor.data
val lonarr = calc_moments(0)("lon").tensor.data
val zipped = std.zip(skw)

%md
####Perform k-means clustering on the PDF moments
We now perform kmeans. Note that this is the same parallel kmeans implementation that Pyspark uses.
This is because Pyspark interfaces with Mllib's scala api for Kmeans clustering.

paragraphs.text:
val numClusters = 5
val iter = 300

val vectors = sc.parallelize(zipped).map{ case (std_i, sk_i) => Vectors.dense(std_i, sk_i)}

val clusters = new KMeans().setSeed(0).setMaxIterations(iter).setK(numClusters).run(vectors)
val centers = clusters.clusterCenters.toList
val prd = clusters.predict(vectors).collect

%md
####Record and Visualize
We now record our results and write it into NetCDF files. 
These pieces of code are quite verbose, and will be soon abstracted into the sRDD and SciTensor.
We then read the NetCDF file from python and use matplotlib to visualize our results.

val writer = NetcdfFileWriter.createNew(NetcdfFileWriter.Version.netcdf3, "results", null)
val xDim = writer.addDimension(null, "len", std.length)
val centerDim = writer.addDimension(null, "len_centers", centers.length)
val latDim = writer.addDimension(null, "latDim", latarr.length)
val lonDim = writer.addDimension(null, "lonDim", lonarr.length)
val dims = new util.ArrayList[Dimension]()
val cDim = new util.ArrayList[Dimension]()
val latDims = new util.ArrayList[Dimension]()
val lonDims = new util.ArrayList[Dimension]()
dims.add(xDim)
cDim.add(centerDim)
latDims.add(latDim)
lonDims.add(lonDim)
val std_var = writer.addVariable(null, "std", DataType.DOUBLE, dims)
val skw_var = writer.addVariable(null, "skw", DataType.DOUBLE, dims)
val prd_var = writer.addVariable(null, "prediction", DataType.INT, dims)
val cnt_std_var = writer.addVariable(null, "centers_std", DataType.DOUBLE, cDim)
val cnt_skw_var = writer.addVariable(null, "centers_skw", DataType.DOUBLE, cDim)
val lat_dim_var = writer.addVariable(null, "lat", DataType.DOUBLE, latDims)
val lon_dim_var = writer.addVariable(null, "lon", DataType.DOUBLE, lonDims)
writer.create()

val stddataOut = new ArrayDouble.D1(std.length)
val skwdataOut = new ArrayDouble.D1(skw.length)
val prdDataOut = new ArrayInt.D1(prd.length)
val cnt_stdDataOut = new ArrayDouble.D1(centers.length)
val cnt_skwDataOut = new ArrayDouble.D1(centers.length)
val latdataOut = new ArrayDouble.D1(latarr.length)
val londataOut = new ArrayDouble.D1(lonarr.length)
assert(std.length == skw.length && skw.length == prd.length)
for(i <- 0 until std.length){
    stddataOut.set(i, std(i))
    skwdataOut.set(i, skw(i))
    prdDataOut.set(i, prd(i))
}

for(i <- 0 until centers.length){
    cnt_stdDataOut.set(i, centers(i)(0))
    cnt_skwDataOut.set(i, centers(i)(1))
}

for(i <- 0 until latarr.length){
    latdataOut.set(i, latarr(i))
}

for(i <- 0 until lonarr.length){
    londataOut.set(i, lonarr(i))
}
    
writer.write(std_var, stddataOut)
writer.write(skw_var, skwdataOut)
writer.write(prd_var, prdDataOut)
writer.write(lat_dim_var, latdataOut)
writer.write(lon_dim_var, londataOut)
writer.write(cnt_std_var, cnt_stdDataOut)
writer.write(cnt_skw_var, cnt_skwDataOut)

writer.close()

paragraphs.title: Matplotlib functions to visualize the netcdf
paragraphs.text: %pyspark import matplotlib as mpl mpl.use('Agg') import matplotlib.pyplot as plt import cStringIO import base64 import numpy as np from netCDF4 import Dataset from mpl_toolkits.basemap import Basemap def show(p): img = cStringIO.StringIO() p.savefig(img, format='png') imgStr = "data:image/png;base64," imgStr += base64.b64encode(img.getvalue().strip()) print "%html " def visualize_clusters(centroids, labels, moments, lats, lons, ptitle='', cmap='rainbow_r'): ''' Visualize the k clusters on a map. Input: centroids - locations of cluster centroids (k, 2) labels - group number for each grid point (gridpoints) moments - dict where values are moment numpy arrays and keys are the name of each moment (eg. 'Skewness') lats, lons - 1 or 2D numpy arrays of lat/lon information (Optional) title - Plot title (string) ''' if lats.ndim == 1: nx, ny = len(lons), len(lats) else: nx, ny = lons.shape[1], lats.shape[0] # Reshape so clusters are on a 2D grid clusters = labels.reshape(ny, nx) + 1 k = centroids.shape[0] # Make Plots fig, plot_grid = plt.subplots(nrows=2, ncols=2) fig.set_size_inches((11, 7)) plt.subplots_adjust(wspace=0.2, hspace=0.2) # Set up the color scaling cmap = plt.get_cmap(cmap) norm = mpl.colors.BoundaryNorm(1 + np.arange(k+1), cmap.N) # Upper Left: Map of clusters lon_min = lons.min() lon_max = lons.max() lat_min = lats.min() lat_max = lats.max() m = Basemap(projection='cyl', llcrnrlat=lat_min, urcrnrlat=lat_max, llcrnrlon=lon_min, urcrnrlon=lon_max, resolution='l') m.ax = plot_grid[0, 0] if lats.ndim == 1: lons, lats = np.meshgrid(lons, lats) x, y = m(lons, lats) clevs = 0.5 + np.arange(k+1) m.drawcoastlines(linewidth=1) m.drawcountries(linewidth=.75) m.contourf(x, y, clusters, levels=clevs, cmap=cmap, norm=norm, alpha=0.5) m.ax.set_title('Clusters') # Upper Right: Scatter Plot of clusters ax = plot_grid[0,1] m1, m2 = moments.values() m1 = m1.ravel() m2 = m2.ravel() name1, name2 = moments.keys() clusters = clusters.ravel() ax.scatter(m1, m2, s=.5, edgecolor='none', c=clusters, marker='o', cmap=cmap, norm=norm, alpha=0.5) ax.set_title('Cluster Legend') ax.set_aspect('equal') # Label each cluster centroid for i in 1 + np.arange(5): xm = m1[clusters==i].mean() ym = m2[clusters==i].mean() ax.plot(xm, ym, marker='$%d$' %(i), markersize=12, color='k') ax.set_xlabel(name1) ax.set_ylabel(name2) # Bottom: Plot moments for ax, moment, name in zip(plot_grid[1, :], moments.values(), moments.keys()): m.ax = ax m.drawcoastlines(linewidth=1) m.drawcountries(linewidth=.75) cs = m.contourf(x, y, moment, 20) m.colorbar(cs, location='bottom', ax=ax) m.ax.set_title(name) # Title and save the figure fig.suptitle(ptitle) show(plt)

%pyspark
nc = Dataset('results')
std = nc['std'][:].reshape(181, 286)
sk = nc['skw'][:].reshape(181, 286)
labels = nc['prediction'][:]
centroids = np.array(zip(nc['centers_std'][:], nc['centers_skw'][:]))
print(centroids)
lats = nc['lat'][:]
lons = nc['lon'][:]
moments = {'Standard Deviation':std, 'Skewness':sk}
title = 'MERRA Jan. Surface Temperature (1979-2011)'
fname = 'MERRA_cluster.png'
visualize_clusters(centroids, labels, moments, lats, lons, ptitle=title)
